a safe place.

250
00:11:54,776 --> 00:11:58,071
And, Morgan, perhaps
if you're looking to be challenged,

251
00:11:58,572 --> 00:12:02,576
finding outlets outside the relationship
might allow for more…

252
00:12:03,618 --> 00:12:05,954
patience and warmth with Max, which…

253
00:12:07,247 --> 00:12:09,124
It's a different kind of excitement.

254
00:12:09,708 --> 00:12:13,920
I just want you to look at me
the way that you used to look at me.

255
00:12:14,504 --> 00:12:15,756
I want that too.

256
00:12:16,423 --> 00:12:19,342
Okay, when she ended things
after high school and moved to New York,

257
00:12:19,426 --> 00:12:22,095
I thought, "Wow,
what a fucking bitch." Right?

258
00:12:22,179 --> 00:12:26,057
But also, like, "There goes the most
interesting person I've ever met."

259
00:12:29,394 --> 00:12:34,524
[exhales] You're saying it like
it's like I did something special.

260
00:12:34,608 --> 00:12:36,610
New York is, like,
a 30-minute train ride from here.

261
00:12:36,693 --> 00:12:38,653
Okay, but people don't just
do that, Morgan.

262
00:12:38,737 --> 00:12:42,407
They don't just, like, oh, leave home
to go pursue their dreams.

263
00:12:43,408 --> 00:12:44,618
[sighs] Yeah--

264
00:12:44,701 --> 00:12:47,120
Then I didn't book any jobs
and I ran out of money, so, yeah…

265
00:12:47,204 --> 00:12:48,413
Who fucking cares?

266
00:12:49,247 --> 00:12:51,583
Who cares?
You have all these worldly experiences.

267
00:12:51,666 --> 00:12:54,461
I want to experience
something worldly with you

268
00:12:54,544 --> 00:12:57,130
that isn't just my mom taking us to Cabo.

269
00:12:57,214 --> 00:13:00,175
-We should go to fucking Burning Man.
-[cell phone ringing]

270
00:13:00,258 --> 00:13:03,720
We're not gonna go to Burning Man,
but I get what you're saying, you know?

271
00:13:03,804 --> 00:13:07,057
Like, I understand. I'm so sorry.
I'm just gonna step out for one second.

272
00:13:07,140 --> 00:13:09,810
I just have to take this,
but I'm-- I'm really sorry.

273
00:13:10,435 --> 00:13:13,230
-[ringing continues]
-I think you both want the same things.

274
00:13:13,313 --> 00:13:15,148
[funky music playing]

275
00:13:16,566 --> 00:13:18,235
[Morgan] Okay, what is up with you?

276
00:13:19,152 --> 00:13:20,237
What do you mean?

277
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:22,656
Uh, I don't know. Something is off.

278
00:13:23,281 --> 00:13:25,784
You-- you haven't complained once.
You're borderline pleasant.

279
00:13:25,867 --> 00:13:28,119
I'm having a nice day, okay?

280
00:13:28,203 --> 00:13:31,915
I realize that there's no point
in making our situation any worse

281
00:13:31,998 --> 00:13:33,124
than it already is.

282
00:13:33,208 --> 00:13:35,418
We don't actually know
if these people are criminals.

283
00:13:35,502 --> 00:13:37,838
I mean, you know… I… I don't know.

284
00:13:37,921 --> 00:13:42,175
They could just be overextended
and needing a few extra hands.

285
00:13:42,259 --> 00:13:43,093
That's…

286
00:13:43,176 --> 00:13:47,347
We are driving to pick up a stranger
from prison. Are you okay?

287
00:13:47,430 --> 00:13:50,183
-I'm leaning into joy today, Morgan.
-[exhales loudly]

288
00:13:50,267 --> 00:13:54,396
I'm trying to have a nice, happy,
meaningful life today.

289
00:13:54,479 --> 00:13:56,314
-[inhales]
-Don't you find it demeaning, though?

290
00:13:56,398 --> 00:13:58,400
That they send us
on these little gofer errands.

291
00:13:58,483 --> 00:14:00,277
It's like they think
we're not capable of more.

292
00:14:00,360 --> 00:14:03,864
We don't want them thinking we're capable
of more, Morgan. Why would we want that?

293
00:14:03,947 --> 00:14:07,158
I don't know. If you're gonna send me
to the strip club, put me on the pole.

294
00:14:07,242 --> 00:14:08,869
-You know?
-I've never had that thought.

295
00:14:08,952 --> 00:14:10,954
[Morgan] And what even is
a medium-security prison?

296
00:14:11,037 --> 00:14:13,415
Like, what do you even have to do
to be "mediumly" secured?

297
00:14:13,498 --> 00:14:15,166
[Nicky] I don't-- I don't care.

298
00:14:15,250 --> 00:14:17,377
-It's a very organized system.
-[guard] Ma'am.

299
00:14:18,712 --> 00:14:20,255
-Pop the trunk.
-Oh.

300
00:14:20,338 --> 00:14:21,882
-[Morgan clears throat]
-Pop the trunk.

301
00:14:21,965 --> 00:14:22,799
[trunk opens]

302
00:14:22,883 --> 00:14:24,551
[Morgan exhales] It's strict here.

303
00:14:24,634 --> 00:14:26,261
[speaking indistinctly over PA]

304
00:14:26,970 --> 00:14:29,347
-Do you have anything in your trunk?
-No.

305
00:14:29,431 --> 00:14:30,557
[trunk closes]

306
00:14:30,640 --> 00:14:32,809
-[Nicky] Is there anything in there?
-[Morgan] No.

307
00:14:33,894 --> 00:14:35,270
-[guard] Ma'am.
-Mm-hmm.

308
00:14:35,353 --> 00:14:39,316
Are you aware that you have six cases
of Four Loko in the trunk of your car?

309
00:14:39,399 --> 00:14:40,275
[sighs loudly]

310
00:14:40,358 --> 00:14:41,818
-What?
-Fucking Max.

311
00:14:41,902 --> 00:14:44,446
-Who drinks that?
-[spluttering] No, I wasn't aware of that.

312
00:14:44,529 --> 00:14:46,448
I can't let you in
with drinks in your trunk.

313
00:14:46,531 --> 00:14:48,533
-[Morgan] Come on.
-I'm gonna have to walk, then.

314
00:14:48,617 --> 00:14:50,327
Uh, no, I'll go. I'll go. I'll do it.

315
00:14:50,410 --> 00:14:52,829
As much as I'd love
to send you into a prison,

316
00:14:52,913 --> 00:14:56,374
Reverend Dardano is supposed to be
picking up an incarcerated parishioner…

317
00:14:56,458 --> 00:14:58,418
-[exhales loudly]
-…he's been counseling, okay? So.

318
00:14:58,501 --> 00:14:59,502
This sucks.

319
00:14:59,586 --> 00:15:00,462
Say a prayer.

320
00:15:04,132 --> 00:15:05,258
Do I have to go around?

321
00:15:05,342 --> 00:15:07,636
[quietly] Hi, I'm here
to take you to your apartment

322
00:15:07,719 --> 00:15:11,473
and offer whatever rehabilitative--
reha-- rehabilitative services…

323
00:15:11,556 --> 00:15:13,516
-[alarm buzzing]
-[gate creaking]

324
00:15:13,600 --> 00:15:14,434
Okay.

325
00:15:14,517 --> 00:15:15,810
[sniffs, clears throat]

326
00:15:15,894 --> 00:15:16,853
[gate creaking]

327
00:15:17,479 --> 00:15:19,522
-[gate clanging]
-[alarm buzzing]

328
00:15:21,441 --> 00:15:22,776
Hello.

329
00:15:24,235 --> 00:15:25,654
Are you… are you Andrei?

330
00:15:26,363 --> 00:15:27,322
Who the fuck are you?

331
00:15:27,405 --> 00:15:29,532
Oh, I'm, um… I'm Pastor Dardano.

332
00:15:31,034 --> 00:15:33,954
I'm here to take you
to your new apartment, um,

333
00:15:34,037 --> 00:15:38,458
and offer whatever rehabilitative services
you would like for your reentry.

334
00:15:39,084 --> 00:15:41,461
Um, do you have
everything you need, or…?

335
00:15:41,544 --> 00:15:42,504
Where's Ivan?

336
00:15:42,587 --> 00:15:43,964
Oh, right. Um…

337
00:15:44,839 --> 00:15:47,634
[whispers] Ivan thought it would be better
if I came to pick you up,

338
00:15:47,717 --> 00:15:48,885
just optically speaking.

339
00:15:48,969 --> 00:15:50,553
-Why are you whispering?
-I don't know.

340
00:15:50,637 --> 00:15:52,973
I'm not quite sure
why I'm whispering, actually.

341
00:15:53,056 --> 00:15:54,015
Where's the car?

342
00:15:54,099 --> 00:15:59,062
Oh, okay, so we couldn't park in here,
so it's just a quick 10 to 15 this way.

343
00:15:59,145 --> 00:16:01,731
-If you want to come with-- Okay.
-[speaking Russian]

344
00:16:01,815 --> 00:16:02,691
[Andrei clears throat]

345
00:16:02,774 --> 00:16:04,567
[tense music playing]

346
00:16:04,651 --> 00:16:06,653
-[Andrei inhales sharply]
-Mm-hmm.

347
00:16:07,529 --> 00:16:09,614
You must be relieved to be out of prison.

348
00:16:09,698 --> 00:16:11,324
-I don't wanna talk!
-Okay.

349
00:16:11,408 --> 00:16:13,243
-[indistinct chattering]
-[camera clicking]

350
00:16:13,827 --> 00:16:14,703
Linda.

351
00:16:14,786 --> 00:16:16,871
Oh, hi. Hi, Annette.

352
00:16:16,955 --> 00:16:19,040
-Hi.
-You look fabulous.

353
00:16:19,124 --> 00:16:21,710
Oh, thank you, Annette. [laughs]

354
00:16:21,793 --> 00:16:23,837
[moderator] All right, everyone,
settle down, please.

355
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:25,338
-Settle down.
-[door closes]

356
00:16:25,422 --> 00:16:28,800
First of all, I would like to thank
the both of you for being here today.

357
00:16:28,883 --> 00:16:31,636
-Thank you for having us both.
-Of course, glad to be here.

358
00:16:31,720 --> 00:16:32,554
[coughing]

359
00:16:32,637 --> 00:16:35,724
[moderator] All right, well,
let me begin with an easy question

360
00:16:35,807 --> 00:16:36,933
to get things rolling.

361
00:16:37,767 --> 00:16:41,104
What distinguishes each of you
from the other candidate?

362
00:16:41,187 --> 00:16:43,023
-Linda, we'll start with you.
-Yes.

363
00:16:43,106 --> 00:16:45,692
I know-- Thank you for the question, Jane.

364
00:16:45,775 --> 00:16:48,445
I know this town like the back of my hand.

365
00:16:48,528 --> 00:16:50,405
I was born here. Um…

366
00:16:50,488 --> 00:16:55,243
My family has owned Morelli's Hardware
for over 70 years. [laughs]

367
00:16:55,326 --> 00:16:59,581
I raised my kids here,
and I have watched this town grow,

368
00:16:59,664 --> 00:17:01,833
which is why I have a strong desire

369
00:17:01,916 --> 00:17:04,544
to preserve the Glenview
that I know and love

370
00:17:04,627 --> 00:17:08,548
and to restore
a sense of safety and security

371
00:17:08,631 --> 00:17:11,301
that has long been associated with it.

372
00:17:11,384 --> 00:17:15,889
Just last week, my son was assaulted
on the street for being gay.

373
00:17:15,972 --> 00:17:17,932
That is not the town that I know.

374
00:17:18,016 --> 00:17:20,268
That is not the town that I love.

375
00:17:20,351 --> 00:17:25,940
Now more than ever, we need a leader
who has seen this town at its very best.

376
00:17:26,941 --> 00:17:28,526
[moderator] Tom, same question.

377
00:17:29,027 --> 00:17:31,654
Well, first off, I just want to say
that I find it heartbreaking

378
00:17:31,738 --> 00:17:34,741
that Linda Morelli doesn't seem
to like this town very much. [chuckles]

379
00:17:34,824 --> 00:17:36,326
-[audience muttering]
-[Tom] Hmm?

380
00:17:36,409 --> 00:17:39,120
I happen to love this town.
Always have, always will.

381
00:17:39,204 --> 00:17:40,872
That's not, uh, what I said in the--

382
00:17:40,955 --> 00:17:45,001
Sorry, Linda. It is Tom's time to answer
the question. You will get a rebuttal.

383
00:17:45,085 --> 00:17:46,294
-[Tom] Well…
-But I didn't--

384
00:17:46,377 --> 00:17:48,296
Let me just say… [chuckles]

385
00:17:48,379 --> 00:17:51,299
I am in agreement.
Hate crimes have no place in this town.

386
00:17:51,382 --> 00:17:52,801
-Well, duh.
-Well…

387
00:17:52,884 --> 00:17:55,929
But do we really want
someone's mom dictating policy

388
00:17:56,012 --> 00:17:58,014
based on what happens to her kids?

389
00:17:58,098 --> 00:17:59,974
I mean, if her daughter gets a flat tire,

390
00:18:00,058 --> 00:18:03,436
will we suddenly
have to, uh, repave every road?

391
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:06,397
Sorry, Tom, but, uh, is that your answer

392
00:18:06,481 --> 00:18:10,568
to what distinguishes you
as a… a candidate?

393
00:18:10,652 --> 00:18:14,989
Because, um, it's easy to critique
somebody else's answer

394
00:18:15,073 --> 00:18:17,242
when you haven't an-- answered one.

395
00:18:17,325 --> 00:18:20,870
Wow, see, I didn't know you were running
for the job of moderator. Huh.

396
00:18:20,954 --> 00:18:22,163
[chuckles] Watch out, Jane.

397
00:18:22,247 --> 00:18:26,334
[inhales] Uh, okay. Well,
as the owner of 38 Jimmy John's,

398
00:18:26,417 --> 00:18:30,421
my employee count is ten times
the size of this city council

399
00:18:30,505 --> 00:18:33,967
and likely 20 times the size
of whoever Linda's got on staff

400
00:18:34,050 --> 00:18:35,969
at her little, uh, shop. [inhales]

401
00:18:36,052 --> 00:18:39,597
I know how to manage people,
and I know how to manage places.

402
00:18:39,681 --> 00:18:42,183
My opponent, who seems very nice,

403
00:18:42,267 --> 00:18:45,061
feels better suited to run
our neighborhood watch programs

404
00:18:45,145 --> 00:18:47,063
than lead our entire municipal government.

405
00:18:47,147 --> 00:18:49,190
[hoarsely] Tom,
you better be careful there,

406
00:18:49,274 --> 00:18:51,734
because you're starting to sound
a little bit misogynistic.

407
00:18:51,818 --> 00:18:54,779
Uh-oh. There it is.
I've awoken the beast. [laughs]

408
00:18:55,405 --> 00:18:57,157
We get it, Linda. You're tough.

409
00:18:57,240 --> 00:19:01,327
I'm starting to understand how you managed
to scare off the chief of police. [laughs]

410
00:19:01,411 --> 00:19:02,412
[tense music playing]

411
00:19:02,495 --> 00:19:03,913
Excuse me?

412
00:19:04,414 --> 00:19:06,749
-[Natalie gasping]
-[audience muttering]

413
00:19:07,333 --> 00:19:08,585
[cameras clicking]

414
00:19:09,169 --> 00:19:10,587
[music ends]

415
00:19:14,549 --> 00:19:15,842
[lighter clicks]

416
00:19:23,433 --> 00:19:24,767
Morgan, he's smoking in the car.

417
00:19:24,851 --> 00:19:26,311
-Put the window down.
-Yeah.

418
00:19:27,979 --> 00:19:30,064
[Nicky coughs]

419
00:19:30,148 --> 00:19:32,150
-[Nicky whispers] Jesus.
-[window whirring]

420
00:19:32,233 --> 00:19:34,194
He put the window back up. Can you--

421
00:19:34,277 --> 00:19:36,029
-What is going on here?
-Okay.

422
00:19:36,112 --> 00:19:38,114
-[window opening]
-[car speeding by]

423
00:19:38,781 --> 00:19:39,991
So, um… [clears throat]

424
00:19:40,074 --> 00:19:41,284
What were you in for?

425
00:19:41,367 --> 00:19:43,369
-It's better you don't know.
-Okay.

426
00:19:43,453 --> 00:19:45,413
-Okay, that's the scariest answer…
-[phone ringing]

427
00:19:45,496 --> 00:19:46,748
…you could've possibly given me.

428
00:19:46,831 --> 00:19:48,666
-Thank you.
-Oh, God.

429
00:19:49,500 --> 00:19:51,753
Yeah, we have him.
We're… We're driving to the apartment.

430
00:19:51,836 --> 00:19:53,755
-No, you're not.
-What do you mean, "we're not"?

431
00:19:53,838 --> 00:19:56,507
-Put him on speakerphone.
-What do you mean? What--

432
00:19:56,591 --> 00:19:59,177
What do you mean, "No, we're not"?
We're… we're in the car with him.

433
00:19:59,260 --> 00:20:00,678
[Yusuf] No, you're fucking not!

434
00:20:00,762 --> 00:20:02,680
The apartment won't be ready
until tomorrow

435
00:20:02,764 --> 00:20:05,225
because someone asked
to have it fucking repainted.

436
00:20:06,267 --> 00:20:07,560
[whispers] Don't put this on me.

437
00:20:07,644 --> 00:20:10,271
Okay. Well, how long does it take
to paint an apartment?

438
00:20:10,355 --> 00:20:13,066
He says two coats.
There's no point in only doing one.

439
00:20:13,149 --> 00:20:15,526
-I've slept in worse.
-[Yusuf] He won't let me in.

440
00:20:15,610 --> 00:20:17,737
-The walls are wet. The room stinks.
-[phone buzzing]

441
00:20:17,820 --> 00:20:19,405
[angrily] Who the fuck asked for paint?

442
00:20:19,489 --> 00:20:21,741
-I'm not in… I don't-- I don't know, okay?
-Hi, Mom.

443
00:20:21,824 --> 00:20:24,994
Morgan, what are you doing
on Nicholas's phone? Put me on speaker.

444
00:20:25,078 --> 00:20:27,330
-Oh, I don't think that works right now.
-Hold please.

445
00:20:27,413 --> 00:20:30,959
No, Morgan, this is a crisis.
I need to talk to both of you.

446
00:20:31,042 --> 00:20:32,669
-What is she saying?
-[exhales] Okay.

447
00:20:32,752 --> 00:20:36,923
The debate was a disaster. We're having
an emergency family dinner at the house.

448
00:20:37,006 --> 00:20:39,342
Hello? Who the fuck is that?
Who else is in the car?

449
00:20:39,425 --> 00:20:40,885
Nobody else is in the car.

450
00:20:40,969 --> 00:20:42,887
Someone else is in the car? Where are you?

451
00:20:42,971 --> 00:20:45,807
Ma, tonight doesn't really work for me,
because I promised Max

452
00:20:45,890 --> 00:20:47,684
we were gonna have a romantic night in.

453
00:20:47,767 --> 00:20:49,811
[Linda] Uh, okay, well, Nicky,
be here in 30 minutes.

454
00:20:49,894 --> 00:20:51,854
-Who is this woman?
-I hear someone's voice.

455
00:20:51,938 --> 00:20:53,815
Who the fuck is talking right now?

456
00:20:53,898 --> 00:20:56,442
No-- Nobody's talking. It's--
Mom, I'm with a parishioner, okay?

457
00:20:56,526 --> 00:20:59,404
I don't think I'm gonna be home,
so I… I… I don't think I can make dinner.

458
00:20:59,487 --> 00:21:02,365
No, Nicholas! This is nonnegotiable.

459
00:21:02,448 --> 00:21:06,953
I got raked over the coals
by a sandwich king at the debate.

460
00:21:07,036 --> 00:21:09,539
-What? What is she talking about?
-[Linda] I need some help here.

461
00:21:09,622 --> 00:21:11,499
If you need to,
bring your friend to dinner.

462
00:21:11,582 --> 00:21:12,542
He's not my friend.

463
00:21:12,625 --> 00:21:16,629
But be here by 7:00. You know
how I hate using the warming drawer.

464
00:21:16,713 --> 00:21:17,964
-Lady.
-Is that your friend?

465
00:21:18,047 --> 00:21:19,716
Tell him I'm making chicken cacciatore.

466
00:21:19,799 --> 00:21:21,926
[Yusuf] I don't know
what the fuck is going on.

467
00:21:22,010 --> 00:21:25,263
But someone take me the fucking off
of speakerphone right now!

468
00:21:25,346 --> 00:21:29,142
He called me an animal.
It was humiliating.

469
00:21:29,225 --> 00:21:31,352
Well, what made him say that?
Were you yelling at him?

470
00:21:31,436 --> 00:21:33,313
[yelling] Was I yelling at him?

471
00:21:33,396 --> 00:21:35,315
No, I was defending myself,

472
00:21:35,398 --> 00:21:38,985
and on top of that,
he added absolutely nothing of value

473
00:21:39,068 --> 00:21:43,281
except that his grandfather
apparently invented the French dip.

474
00:21:43,364 --> 00:21:47,493
But the most disturbing part of it was,
people seemed to side with him.

475
00:21:47,577 --> 00:21:48,703
[Andrei moans]

476
00:21:48,786 --> 00:21:51,622
This is the most delicious chicken
I've ever had.

477
00:21:51,706 --> 00:21:54,751
Every night I've dreamed
of a meal like this.

478
00:21:54,834 --> 00:21:56,544
-[Natalie] Oh.
-[Andrei chewing]

479
00:21:57,211 --> 00:21:58,463
[whispers] I think he's crying.

